alfe-backend-clautolisp — in-process and subprocess clautolisp backends
=======================================================================

See also: alfe.plan, alfe-backend-interface.issue, alfe-cli.issue,
spec section "Backend clautolisp".

Context
-------

The clautolisp backend is the simplest of the three because
clautolisp itself is a Common Lisp process: alfe can either *be*
that process (in-process, default) or *spawn* it as a subprocess
(`uiop:launch-program`) and talk to it via stdin/stdout pipes. Both
paths skip the file-IPC protocol entirely — that protocol exists
only because the CAD backends have no alternative.

This issue lands the clautolisp backend. With it, V1 success
criterion `alfe --clautolisp -x '(+ 1 2)'` works end-to-end.

In scope
--------

  1. In-process backend (`alfe.backend.clautolisp.direct`):
       - Implements every generic from `alfe-backend-interface.issue`.
       - `start-engine` calls
         `clautolisp.autolisp-runtime:make-default-runtime-context`
         with the requested dialect, installs the core builtins via
         `clautolisp.autolisp-builtins-core:install-core-builtins`,
         attaches the HAL backend (defaults to MockHost when
         `--host mock`, NullHost when `--host null`).
       - `eval-plan` walks the action records and dispatches:
           (:load PATH ENC)  → run-autolisp-file
           (:eval EXPR)      → run-autolisp-string
           (:main SYMBOL)    → look up + call
           (:interactive)    → REPL loop using autolisp-reader for
                                form-completeness; multi-line forms
                                join until balanced.
       - Output capture: bind `*standard-output*` / `*error-output*`
         around the eval so that, in addition to writing to the live
         terminal streams, the same text is mirrored into
         `WORKDIR/output.txt` and `WORKDIR/errors.txt` for diagnostic
         symmetry with the CAD backends (the spec already documents
         this).
       - `request-control INTERRUPT` flips a special variable that
         user code can consult; `SHUTDOWN` triggers graceful exit
         from the REPL loop.

  2. Subprocess backend (`alfe.backend.clautolisp.subprocess`):
       - `start-engine` spawns `clautolisp-sbcl --quiet --dialect
         <D>` via `uiop:launch-program`, gets stdin/stdout/stderr
         handles.
       - `eval-plan` writes the same action plan to the subprocess
         stdin, line by line, using clautolisp's existing REPL
         banner conventions; tags each form with a sentinel so
         output framing is unambiguous on read-back.
       - `read-output` drains the subprocess stdout / stderr.
       - `shutdown` writes a clean exit sentinel and waits up to
         `--timeout` seconds for the process; SIGTERM/SIGKILL escape
         hatch on timeout.
       - Useful when the host Lisp differs from the wanted dialect
         host, or when one wants alfe and clautolisp to live in
         separate address spaces (e.g. when alfe drives multiple
         clautolisp instances concurrently — out of scope for V1 but
         the design should not preclude it).

  3. Backend selection in the CLI:
       - `--clautolisp` selects the *direct* variant by default.
       - `--clautolisp --backend subprocess` selects the subprocess
         variant.
       - `alfe.backend.detect` for clautolisp always succeeds (no
         external dependency); the detector merely returns the
         configured variant.

  4. Encoding. `-e` (load encoding) and `-E` (I/O encoding) are
     plumbed via `babel` / Lisp external-formats; tests cover
     `:utf-8`, `:iso-8859-1`, `:windows-1252` with LF / CRLF / CR
     line endings (mirrors the spec's "Invariants testés").

  5. Tests under `tests/backend-clautolisp-tests.lisp`:
       - one-shot `-x '(+ 1 2)'` returns 3, exit 0 ;
       - `-l fixture.lsp` evaluates side-effects ;
       - `--main C:MAIN` calls the entry point ;
       - `-i` accepts a multi-line form (the canonical
         `(loop (print (eval (read))))` shape, terminated by a
         sentinel) ;
       - encoding round-trips for the three encodings × three line
         endings.

Out of scope
------------

  - HAL backends beyond `MockHost` and `NullHost`. Real CAD HAL
    bridges are tracked separately.
  - `vlisp-compile`. Spec confirms it stays an
    `--autocad --mode automation` Windows-only feature.

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - `alfe --clautolisp -x '(+ 1 2)'` prints 3 and exits 0.
  - `alfe --clautolisp -l fixture.lsp` runs the file and exits with
    the status it set.
  - `alfe --clautolisp --backend subprocess -x '(+ 1 2)'` produces
    identical stdout/stderr to the direct variant.
  - `alfe --clautolisp -i` opens a working REPL with multi-line
    form support inherited from autolisp-reader.
  - The autolisp-test conformance corpus runs green against
    `alfe --clautolisp --host mock`.
  - FiveAM coverage for the encoding matrix + the four action
    kinds passes.

Notes
-----

The direct backend is essentially "alfe's CLI driving the same APIs
that `tools/clautolisp/source/main.lisp` already drives". It is OK
to refactor shared code into `clautolisp` or a new common module if
the duplication becomes painful — but resist doing so pre-emptively;
the two CLIs may diverge naturally in their option sets.
